---

<ChapterShell chapterId="01" locale="en">
  <div slot="thesis">
    <p>
      Without a replayable fact ledger there is no debuggable, projectable, or evolvable Agent. This
      chapter establishes the Runtime Event Log as the canonical source—through the execution spine,
      dual-stream bridge, single-terminal invariant, permission as control flow, and the request
      materialization cost spine—and why Session / UI / Provider contexts can only be projections.
      Keystone: <strong>Log is the source of truth; state is a materialized view.</strong>
    </p>
  </div>

  <Section
    id="scene"
    label="§01 · Scene"
    title="Start from a deceptively simple request"
    lede="An Agent is not “how to call an LLM once”; it is how an open loop becomes replayable history."
  >
    <p>
      Suppose the user says: find the failing tests, fix them, and run again. A chat app only needs
      “send to model → wait → display.” A real Agent must read the project, call tools, wait on
      authorization, handle failure/timeouts, feed results back, loop for many rounds, and terminate
      cleanly as completed / failed / aborted.
    </p>
    <p>The scene immediately exerts open-loop pressures (mechanisms below catch each one):</p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>Streaming output interleaved with stepwise tool side effects;</li>
      <li>Permission is not “UI paused a modal”—it is Runtime control flow;</li>
      <li>After the user stops, a late provider <code>complete</code> must not rewrite the terminal;</li>
      <li>On crash, repair only what is durable—do not invent what the model “was about to do”;</li>
      <li>
        “Shorter prompts” can raise cache miss and bill—request shape is also a Runtime fact surface.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <blockquote class="pull">
      Runtime’s real job: turn an open loop of streaming output, tool side effects, human
      intervention, and process failure into a fact history that can be re-interpreted and replayed.
    </blockquote>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="keystone"
    label="§01 · Keystone"
    title="State is not a table — it is a function of the log"
    lede="Scene-local metaphor; NewsLiquid tokens and hand keystones stay fixed."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      prototype
      caption="Fig 1 · Runtime Events Log at center; Model History / UI / Terminal / Recovery are projections — never reverse-written as truth."
      alt="Center Runtime Events Log with projections to Model History, UI Read Model, Terminal Fact, Recovery/Compact; invariant: log is source of truth."
    >
      <LogIsRuntimeKeystone />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <p>
      Maka’s deepest choice is not which model SDK to use, but:
      <strong
        >the Event Log stores facts; Session, Run, UI, model context, and recovery are consumers or
        projections of that log.</strong
      >
    </p>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="State as projection">State(t) = Project(RuntimeEvents[0..t], policy, runtime configuration)</pre>
    <p class="figure-note">
      Invariant: <strong>Log is the source of truth; state is a materialized view.</strong>
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="spine-consume"
    label="§01 · Spine"
    title="Produce, commit, project, consume"
    lede="The same log can be interpreted into different states — but no consumer may rewrite truth."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig 2 · Produce → Durable append → Project → Consume; the UI transcript is always a consumer, never authority for completed semantics."
      alt="Four-step pipeline: Produce facts, Durable append, Project, Consume views."
    >
      <EventProduceConsumeFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Model History Projector</strong> — messages for the next model call (prune / compact
        may rewrite the projection)
      </li>
      <li><strong>Runtime Read Model</strong> — conversation, tool activity, Turn status for UI</li>
      <li>
        <strong>Terminal Fact Classifier</strong> — a Run’s final outcome (must be backed by a
        terminal RuntimeEvent)
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Recovery</strong> — which facts were durable before exit; repair projections, never
        warm-resume tools
      </li>
      <li><strong>Context / Compaction</strong> — smaller working context that keeps key semantics (§03)</li>
      <li>
        <strong>Cost / request-shape diagnostics</strong> — local diagnostics attached to the real
        assembly path (see <a href="#request-shape">#request-shape</a>)
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Unlike ordinary application logs that describe “what code did” after the fact, RuntimeEvents
      <em>are</em> the business semantics. Delete the log and the system loses any reliable basis to
      rebuild interaction state.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="identities"
    label="§01 · Identity"
    title="Four identities that must not be collapsed"
    lede="A Turn is not a Run; a chat message is not execution state."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig 3 · Session / Turn / Run / Invocation: keep concepts separate so future retries need not rewrite the event protocol."
      alt="Four columns: Session, Turn, Run, Invocation."
    >
      <IdentityLayersFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li><strong>Session</strong> — long-lived interaction ownership (sessionId)</li>
      <li><strong>Turn</strong> — one user-visible Q&amp;A round (turnId)</li>
      <li><strong>Run</strong> — one durable execution attempt (runId / AgentRun)</li>
      <li><strong>Invocation</strong> — Runner’s call boundary (invocationId)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      On the default path runId and invocationId often coincide, but they remain distinct concepts:
      future retries and multi-attempt flows should not force a rewrite of the whole event protocol.
      Without an execution envelope the system only sees “some messages appeared,” never “did this
      execution truly end?”
    </p>
    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">Archive delta · teaching manual</p>
      <p>
        Archive <code>runtime-mainline-teaching-manual.md</code> pins the same split with three mental
        models: user-facing <strong>Turn</strong>, system <strong>Run</strong>, and rebuildable
        <strong>Event ledger</strong>. Chat strings cannot flatten tool calls, permissions, or
        terminals. Current identity/event models follow this chapter and code; the manual is a
        pedagogical delta only.
      </p>
    </aside>
    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">Archive delta · runtime-kernel</p>
      <p>
        Archive <code>runtime-kernel.md</code> explains <strong>why</strong> ToolRuntime /
        ModelAdapter / AgentRun ledger were extracted: after a crash you must answer “did the stream
        start, were we waiting on permission, which tool was in flight, was usage recorded?” — not
        leave those answers smeared across session + backend + wrap logic. Recovery remains
        conservative terminal close (<code>app_restarted</code>), not warm replay. Current authority is
        <a href="#agent-run-recovery">#agent-run-recovery</a> and the code.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="event"
    label="§01 · Event"
    title="What one RuntimeEvent stores"
    lede="Not role + text — orthogonal facts that project, pair, and terminate."
  >
    <p>A durable fact must answer at least these orthogonal dimensions:</p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li><strong>Identity</strong> — session / invocation / run / turn / branch</li>
      <li><strong>Ordering</strong> — id, timestamps, ledger order</li>
      <li><strong>Source</strong> — role, author</li>
      <li><strong>Content</strong> — text, thinking, function call/response, error</li>
      <li>
        <strong>Actions</strong> — state delta, <strong>permission</strong>,
        <strong>artifact</strong>, <strong>usage</strong>, end invocation
      </li>
      <li><strong>Correlation</strong> — tool call, provider event, step, artifact refs</li>
      <li><strong>Lifecycle</strong> — partial stream vs durable fact vs terminal fact</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Actions are not chat text in disguise. Permission request/decision, usage counters, and
      artifact refs enter the ledger as actions so replay can answer why a run stopped, how control
      returned, what it cost, and where evidence lives — without parsing bubble copy.
    </p>
    <p>
      Model history must not be reverse-parsed from the UI transcript; the UI is not the fact source.
      Projectors select non-partial, model-visible events from RuntimeEvents, then materialize per
      provider capability.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="exec-spine"
    label="§01 · Exec spine"
    title="Execution spine: which stability each layer protects"
    lede="Read components as stability boundaries — not class tourism."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig 4 · Caller → SessionManager → Kernel → AgentRun → Runner → AiSdkFlow → Backend / ToolRuntime; each layer protects a different stability."
      alt="Seven-stage execution spine from SessionManager through ToolRuntime."
    >
      <ExecSpineFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Execution spine">Caller
  → SessionManager          # product façade
  → RuntimeKernel           # active-run control plane
  → AgentRun                # durable execution envelope
  → RuntimeRunner           # Invocation protocol
  → AiSdkFlow               # SessionEvent → RuntimeEvent bridge
  → AgentBackend (AiSdkBackend)
       → ModelAdapter       # provider stream normalization
       → ToolRuntime        # side-effect boundary</pre>

    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Component responsibility boundaries" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Component</th>
            <th scope="col">Owns</th>
            <th scope="col">Must not own</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">SessionManager</th>
            <td>Stable <code>sendMessage</code> / stop / recover entry</td>
            <td>Request-shape math, tool loop</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">RuntimeKernel</th>
            <td>Create/register Run, route stop/permission, assemble Runner+Flow, ensure finalize</td>
            <td>Provider stream details</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">AgentRun</th>
            <td>Header lifecycle, initial user RuntimeEvent, history construct, terminal commit</td>
            <td>Choosing the next tool</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">RuntimeRunner</th>
            <td>Preflight rules, require terminal, structured <code>InvocationResult</code></td>
            <td>Calling provider/tools</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">AiSdkFlow</th>
            <td>Map Backend events → canonical facts; <strong>exactly one</strong> terminal</td>
            <td>Re-implementing the model loop</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">AiSdkBackend</th>
            <td>Prompt/history/tools/step loop/usage attach</td>
            <td>Declaring Session-wide active runs</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">ToolRuntime</th>
            <td>Guards, permission, execute, synthetic error results, artifacts</td>
            <td>UI transcript authority</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="stub">
      <p class="stub__tag">Current vs Target</p>
      <p>
        The Runner preflight seam exists; production Kernel may not inject an independent gate yet —
        label “capability present / entry may be unwired,” and do not treat the test contract as a
        full production guarantee.
      </p>
    </div>
    <p>
      Pedagogical failure mode (archive teaching-manual delta): dropping a layer often does
      <strong>not</strong> stop the system immediately — it squeezes responsibility into the wrong
      place (Backend owning active runs, Session strings as terminal truth, or each product shell
      rewriting the agent loop). Layering keeps a shared core reusable while shells (Desktop /
      headless / Harbor) swap only the control plane.
    </p>

    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">History aside · mechanism</p>
      <p>
        Spine wiring:
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/9")}>maka:pr:9</a>
        (Wire AiSdkFlow into SessionManager runtime path),
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/7")}>maka:pr:7</a>
        (Wire RuntimeRunner through SessionManager),
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/6")}>maka:pr:6</a>
        (Fix Runtime v2 runner and flow contracts). Semantic source convergence:
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/14")}>maka:pr:14</a>
        /
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/11")}>maka:pr:11</a>. Docs land (secondary):
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/768")}>maka:pr:768</a>.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="dual-stream"
    label="§01 · Dual stream"
    title="SessionEvent and RuntimeEvent"
    lede="Dual tracks are Current migration reality; Flow is the semantic bridge — not a footnote of shame."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig 5 · Backend still emits SessionEvents; AiSdkFlow maps to RuntimeEvents and enforces a single terminal."
      alt="Three columns: SessionEvent, AiSdkFlow bridge, RuntimeEvent canonical log."
    >
      <DualStreamBridge />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Dual-stream comparison" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Stream</th>
            <th scope="col">Audience</th>
            <th scope="col">Role today</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">SessionEvent</th>
            <td>Renderer / legacy consumers</td>
            <td>Backend still emits these</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">RuntimeEvent</th>
            <td>Canonical semantic log</td>
            <td>Preferred source for completed replay</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>AiSdkFlow mapping beats (must-land for teaching):</p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>text / thinking → model content</li>
      <li>tool_start / tool_result → function call / response</li>
      <li>permission request / decision → actions</li>
      <li>usage → action</li>
      <li>error / abort / complete → failure or terminal facts</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Migration honesty: Flow is still a legacy-to-canonical adapter; Backend does not yet natively
      emit only RuntimeEvents. Dual maintenance cost is a real Current boundary — not a story that
      “only one truth pipe remains.”
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="loop"
    label="§01 · Loop"
    title="How the model ↔ tool loop advances"
    lede="Persist per step; pause the model idle watchdog during tools; still exactly one terminal."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig 6 · Begin → streamText → ToolRuntime (pause idle WD) → next step / finish → Flow single terminal → AgentRun commit."
      alt="Model/tool loop sequence emphasizing per-step persistence and one terminal."
    >
      <ModelToolLoop />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li>Kernel starts Turn → AgentRun.begin</li>
      <li>Runner runs Flow → Backend.send</li>
      <li>streamText → thinking / text / tool call</li>
      <li>ToolRuntime.execute → tool result</li>
      <li>Next step with results</li>
      <li>Final text + finish → SessionEvents</li>
      <li>Flow emits RuntimeEvents + <strong>exactly one</strong> terminal</li>
      <li>AgentRun commits terminal fact + finalize projections</li>
    </ol>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>Persist per-step assistant text/thinking — not one giant final blob.</li>
      <li>Tool calls carry step IDs for replay reassembly.</li>
      <li>
        During tools, pause the model idle watchdog (silence is expected); tool/run timeouts still
        apply.
      </li>
      <li>
        Default step cap (Current policy, e.g. 50): if still tool-calling at cap, keep results + a
        deterministic continue hint rather than an empty UI.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="permission"
    label="§01 · Permission"
    title="Permission is Runtime control flow"
    lede="Permission is control flow. — not “the UI showed a modal.”"
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig 7 · PermissionEngine diamond: allow executes / block writes a synthetic error result / prompt parks while Run keeps its identity."
      alt="Permission control-flow diamond for allow, block, prompt, plus Kernel routing."
    >
      <PermissionControlFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Three permission outcomes" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Result</th>
            <th scope="col">Runtime behavior</th>
            <th scope="col">Ledger</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">allow</th>
            <td>Execute impl</td>
            <td>Decision recorded as needed by policy</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">block</th>
            <td>
              <strong>No</strong> real side effect; write a <strong>synthetic error tool result</strong>
            </td>
            <td>Denial + paired result</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">prompt</th>
            <td>
              Emit permission request; pause watchdog; Session → <code>waiting_for_user</code>; Run
              keeps identity
            </td>
            <td>Request fact; later decision fact</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>
      Routing: <code>RuntimeKernel.respondToPermission()</code> → Backend → ToolRuntime writes the
      decision → continue or deny. Replay/diagnostics must answer why the run stopped and how control
      returned. Pairing with §02: synthetic error results preserve call/result pairing (full protocol
      in §02). Whether an allowed call still needs an OS sandbox wrap is orthogonal — do not conflate
      “user clicked allow” with “unsafe host execution.”
    </p>

    <h3 class="subhead" id="park-remember">Park · remember-for-turn · one-shot escalation</h3>
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 7a · After PROMPT park: remember-for-turn (scope remembered; sibling parks auto-allow) vs one-shot grant (remember forbidden · TTL · single consume)."
      alt="Three boxes: Park Promise; remember-for-turn scope; sandbox escalation one-shot."
    >
      <ParkRememberVsEscalationFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <p>
      <code>prompt</code> parks a Promise in a turn-scoped registry (keyed by <code>requestId</code>);
      Kernel <code>respondToPermission</code> resolves it — Run identity always stays. Ordinary tool
      permission often allows <code>rememberForTurn</code>: allow + remember writes the tool-intent
      <code>scopeKey</code> into this turn’s remembered set and <strong>auto-allows</strong> other
      already-parked prompts with the same scope (parallel <code>browser_*</code> batches need not
      click repeatedly). Sandbox escalation and additional-permission proposals fix
      <code>rememberForTurnAllowed: false</code> — a response carrying <code>rememberForTurn</code>
      throws; the grant binds exact command/cwd/intent (or permissionsHash) and may be
      <strong>consumed once</strong> within TTL. Still-parked requests at turn end reject as user_stop
      / escalation_aborted — never silent allow.
    </p>

    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="remember vs one-shot" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Axis</th>
            <th scope="col">Ordinary permission (remember OK)</th>
            <th scope="col">Escalation / additional (one-shot)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Park</th>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>Yes (same registry, different event.kind)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row"><code>rememberForTurnAllowed</code></th>
            <td>Often true</td>
            <td><strong>Always false</strong></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Grant lifetime</th>
            <td>Turn-scoped scope until turn end</td>
            <td>TTL + single consume; mismatch → typed error</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">After allow</th>
            <td>Still under the normal sandbox profile</td>
            <td>That one call may skip sandbox transform — not a standing unsandboxed mode</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>
      Escalation transform details and the Seatbelt/bwrap selection matrix live in
      <a href="#sandbox">#sandbox</a>; this section only pins “remember ≠ one-shot.” Specimens:
      <code>permission-engine.ts</code> · <code>sandbox-escalation.ts</code> · maka
      <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/1016")}>#1016</a> /
      <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/969")}>#969</a>.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="sandbox"
    label="§01 · Sandbox"
    title="Sandbox is an execution transform, not approval"
    lede="PermissionProfile → SandboxManager.transform → platform argv wrap. Missing backend fails closed — never silent host downgrade."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig 7b · Approval ⊥ sandbox: Engine decides allow/prompt/block; SandboxManager only selects/transforms; shell/PTY/executor owns spawn; escalation grants are one-shot."
      alt="PermissionEngine to PermissionProfile to SandboxManager to spawn owner; escalation one-shot callout."
    >
      <SandboxOwnershipFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <p>
      <code>@maka/core</code> owns the platform-neutral <code>PermissionProfile</code> language
      (managed / disabled / external, plus FS/network policy). <code>@maka/runtime</code>’s
      <code>SandboxManager</code> answers only: does this profile need a sandbox, which backend, how to
      rewrite argv. <strong>It does not spawn, retry unsandboxed, emit UI, or own telemetry.</strong>
      Callers own canonical cwd and <code>SandboxPathContext</code> (workspaceRoots / tmp /
      runtimeReadable / executable); backends must not guess workspace roots.
    </p>

    <h3 class="subhead">Selection matrix (fail-closed)</h3>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Sandbox selection matrix" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Situation</th>
            <th scope="col">Result</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">managed + restricted + <code>auto</code> + darwin</th>
            <td><code>macos-seatbelt</code>: <code>/usr/bin/sandbox-exec</code> + SBPL</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Same, Seatbelt unregistered/unavailable</th>
            <td><code>backend_not_available</code> — no silent host</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">managed + restricted + <code>auto</code> + linux + bwrap available</th>
            <td><code>linux</code>: bubblewrap argv (Current; default manager registers it)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">linux missing bwrap/capability, or deny entries unenforceable</th>
            <td>Typed failure (<code>backend_not_available</code> / <code>invalid_request</code>)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">unrestricted / disabled / external + <code>auto</code></th>
            <td><code>sandboxType: none</code> (External = environment already isolates FS)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row"><code>require</code> on unsupported platform (e.g. win32)</th>
            <td><code>unsupported_platform</code></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row"><code>forbid</code></th>
            <td>Host path; Engine approval still required — forbid ≠ authorized</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>
      Standard profiles: <code>read-only</code> / <code>workspace-write</code> (with deny_write
      metadata for <code>.git</code> / <code>.agents</code> / <code>.codex</code>) /
      <code>danger-full-access</code>. <code>additionalPermissions</code> merge into
      <strong>this transform only</strong>, without mutating the base profile.
    </p>

    <h3 class="subhead">Escalation one-shot</h3>
    <p>
      Bash may declare <code>sandbox_permissions.mode = require_escalated</code> (justification
      required). Planning blocks in explore, may skip in bypass; otherwise PermissionEngine prompts with
      <code>sandbox_escalation</code> (<code>rememberForTurnAllowed: false</code> — contrast with
      ordinary remember-for-turn in <a href="#park-remember">#park-remember</a>). An allow produces a
      grant bound to exact command / cwd / intentHash — <strong>consumable once</strong> within TTL.
      Changed command, second consume, or expiry → <code>command_mismatch</code> /
      <code>grant_consumed</code> / <code>grant_expired</code>. This is one-shot escalation, not a
      standing unsandboxed mode; the proposal’s risk summary honestly flags unrestricted FS/network and
      protected-metadata exposure.
    </p>

    <h3 class="subhead">Three “sandboxes” that must not collapse</h3>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        <strong>OS platform sandbox</strong> (this section) — Seatbelt / bubblewrap argv transform.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>§04 throwaway workspace</strong> — fixture-mutation isolation directory, not a security
        sandbox; see
        <a href={localePath("en", "chapters/04-the-durable-task-loop") + "#workspace"}>§04</a>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>§05 hygiene “sandbox root”</strong> — Heavy-task execution-hygiene report field, not
        Seatbelt.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">History · verification</p>
      <p>
        Contracts live in code + tests: <code>sandbox-manager.test.ts</code>,
        <code>macos-seatbelt*.test.ts</code>, <code>sandbox-escalation.test.ts</code>. Remaining
        enforcement: maka #843. If the local sandbox README still claims Linux
        <code>backend_not_implemented</code>, prefer the <code>LinuxBubblewrapBackend</code> registered by
        the default manager. Managed Bash inserts sandbox via <code>transformCommand</code>; PTY is
        mutually exclusive with mandatory sandbox argv — spawn / live≠result in
        <a href={localePath("en", "chapters/02-evidence-before-compression") + "#shell-side-effects"}
          >§02 · #shell-side-effects</a
        >. File tools add a path-containment leaf plus an optional filesystem worker (protocol v2) —
        see
        <a href={localePath("en", "chapters/02-evidence-before-compression") + "#filesystem-worker"}
          >§02 · #filesystem-worker</a
        >; Desktop SessionManager / IPC composition lives in
        <a href={localePath("en", "guides/desktop-host")}>/guides/desktop-host</a>.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="trust"
    label="§01 · Trust"
    title="Trust boundary: the OS account, not PermissionEngine"
    lede="The only load-bearing boundary against an adversarial LLM is the operating-system user account. In-process screens are UX safety nets, not containment."
  >
    <p>
      Maka is a single-tenant personal desktop assistant; tools run as the user’s OS identity.
      <code>SECURITY.md</code> shares hermes-style honesty: PermissionEngine, output redaction, URL
      allowlists, and WebSearch fail-closed are <strong>valuable</strong>, but they operate on
      attacker-influenced strings — limits of those heuristics are ordinary issues, not “sandbox break”
      narratives.
    </p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Load-bearing:</strong> OS account; <code>credentials.json</code> (dir 0o700 / file
        0o600); Renderer ↔ Main preload IPC (cleartext secrets never flow main→renderer).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Seatbelt / bubblewrap:</strong> code and tests exist; until product compositions route
        command execution through transform, they are <strong>not</strong> a shipped product boundary
        (keep “mechanism ready” separate from “boundary delivered”).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Workspace privacy:</strong>
        <code>WorkspacePrivacyContext = &#123; incognitoActive &#125;</code> is resolved by main;
        renderers must not self-attest. Malformed input fails closed and never defaults to
        <code>false</code>. <code>incognitoActive: false</code> only means incognito did not block —
        each consumer still applies its own settings / permission / retention.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      IM / bot channels are one input surface: credential persistence is separate from long-lived
      bridges; cancel paths use CAS rollback — do not pretend Keychain is already shipped. Protocol
      detail:
      <a href={localePath("en", "guides/bot-im")}>/guides/bot-im</a>.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="terminal"
    label="§01 · Terminal"
    title="Single terminal and late events"
    lede="One terminal. — A terminated Run must have exactly one valid terminal RuntimeEvent; the header must be backed by that fact."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig 8 · Abort accepted first; late complete dashed and silently drained; header/ledger mismatches enter repair."
      alt="Timeline: abort accepted, late complete rejected, three header/ledger failure stories."
    >
      <TerminalRace />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <blockquote class="pull">
      A terminated Run must have exactly one valid terminal RuntimeEvent; the Run header must be
      backed by that fact.
    </blockquote>

    <p>Four failure stories (readers should retell without opening the specimen):</p>
    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li>
        <strong>Double terminal:</strong> Backend emits <code>abort</code> then
        <code>complete(user_stop)</code> → Flow accepts the first; <strong>silently drains</strong>
        late events; aborted semantics win.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Header without ledger:</strong> <code>run.json</code> says completed but no terminal
        RuntimeEvent → do not trust the header; repair toward <code>missing_terminal_event</code>
        failure.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Ledger without header update:</strong> terminal event durable, process dies before
        header → read model treats the terminal event as stronger; recovery repairs the header.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Stop then late complete:</strong> Kernel marks stopped + Backend.stop; late provider
        complete/error cannot resurrect “completed successfully.”
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p>Runner rules worth naming:</p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>Preflight fail → do not start Flow / do not fake a started invocation.</li>
      <li>Initial user RuntimeEvent before Flow events.</li>
      <li>
        Flow throw / no terminal / permission denied / abort / incomplete finish → structured failure.
      </li>
      <li>Success requires non-empty final model text (Current contract).</li>
    </ul>

    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">History aside · mechanism</p>
      <p>
        Repair missing terminal runtime ledgers:
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/410")}>maka:pr:410</a>. Preserve stop semantics for
        synthetic terminals:
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/435")}>maka:pr:435</a>.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="stores"
    label="§01 · Stores"
    title="Authority boundaries of three stores"
    lede="Authority mix-ups are classic bugs: UI projection, ops index, and semantic ledger answer different questions. On-disk ≠ fsync; a torn tail ≠ a legal prefix."
  >
    <h3 id="root-gate" class="subhead">Storage root and single writer</h3>
    <p>
      The interactive root is gated by <code>packages/storage/src/root-authority.ts</code>: marker
      <code>.maka-storage-root.json</code>, interactive write lock, lease. Writers open via
      <code>openInteractiveExecutionStoresForWrite</code>; root-identity drift throws
      <code>StorageRootAuthorityError</code>. Same-key writes are serialized by
      <code>chainWrite</code> (write-queue) — not “anyone may append.”
    </p>

    <h3 id="three-ledgers" class="subhead">What each ledger answers</h3>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Three-store authority" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Store</th>
            <th scope="col">Canonical for</th>
            <th scope="col">Not for</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">SessionStore</th>
            <td>Transcript + header (<code>session.jsonl</code>) · UI / compat projection</td>
            <td>Sole authority for completed semantics; execution terminal truth</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">AgentRunStore</th>
            <td><code>run.json</code> + ops <code>events.jsonl</code> + admissions</td>
            <td>Replacing interaction semantics; treating <code>projections/*</code> as source</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">RuntimeEventStore</th>
            <td>Canonical AI interaction facts (JSONL or SQLite)</td>
            <td>Unlimited partial-delta spam; Settings billing warehouse</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">Archive delta · runtime-v2</p>
      <p>
        Archive <code>runtime-v2-architecture-evolution.md</code> freezes the evolution motive: one run
        was once told through StoredMessage / SessionEvent / AgentRunEvent / RunTrace / telemetry
        <strong>at once</strong> — hard to answer “what is truth?” Current gravity is
        <strong>Invocation + RuntimeEvent + projections</strong>; Session / AgentRun ops / telemetry
        are derived or side ledgers. Layer names follow this chapter and code — not the archive proposal
        diagram.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="File-backed directory sketch">&#123;workspaceRoot&#125;/
  .maka-storage-root.json
  telemetry.json                 # TelemetryRepo (not session JSONL)
  runtime.sqlite                 # optional canonical RuntimeEvent + tool journal
  sessions/&lt;sessionId&gt;/
    session.jsonl                # header + StoredMessage
    task-events.jsonl + tasks.json
    turn-admissions/&lt;turnId&gt;     # RootTurnAdmission (durable)
    runs/&lt;runId&gt;/
      run.json
      events.jsonl               # AgentRun ops
      runtime-events.jsonl       # default RuntimeEvent backplane
      runtime-partials/
    shell-runs/&lt;id&gt;/state.jsonl
  artifacts/…                    # blobs + metadata.jsonl</pre>
    <p>
      Partial streams are bounded, replaceable snapshots; the final non-partial covers the semantic
      slot. Do not treat live deltas as durable truth forever.
    </p>

    <h3 id="durability" class="subhead">What is actually durable: fsync truth</h3>
    <p>
      The primitive is <code>appendJsonl(path, payload, options)</code> (<code>jsonl-append.ts</code>).
      Invariants:
    </p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>Payload <strong>must</strong> end with <code>\n</code> or the call throws.</li>
      <li>
        Flags: <code>O_RDWR | O_APPEND</code> (optional <code>O_CREAT</code>);
        <code>requireExistingRecord</code> forbids an empty file (Session appends).
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>durable: true</code> → <code>handle.sync()</code> +
        <code>syncDirectoryChain(dirname, durabilityRoot)</code>; missing
        <code>durabilityRoot</code> throws; failures wrap as <code>DurableStoreWriteError</code>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>syncDirectoryChain</code> fsyncs directories up to the root; escaping
        <code>durabilityRoot</code> throws. On Windows, directory sync is a no-op (honest limit).
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Durability matrix" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Write path</th>
            <th scope="col">Current durability</th>
            <th scope="col">Honest meaning</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">RuntimeEvent terminal</th>
            <td>
              <code>ensureTerminalRuntimeEventDurable</code> →
              <code>durable: true</code>
            </td>
            <td>File + dir chain; only a final terminal may cross the barrier</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Root-turn admission</th>
            <td><code>writeExclusiveAtomic(..., &#123; durable: true &#125;)</code></td>
            <td>Host <code>turn.start</code> must pass before Run creation</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">
              <code>provider_request_captured</code> (ledger)
            </th>
            <td><code>durable: true</code></td>
            <td>
              Metadata durable; body in artifact (see
              <a href="#usage-stores">#usage-stores</a>)
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">AgentRun ops append</th>
            <td>Caller may pass <code>durable</code></td>
            <td>Not default-on; check the caller</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Session JSONL messages</th>
            <td>Repair yes · <strong>no</strong> default fsync</td>
            <td>Product transcript ≠ execution terminal ledger</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Task / ShellRun / Artifact</th>
            <td>Atomic rename or best-effort; no dir-chain sync</td>
            <td>Contract-complete ≠ power-loss safe</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">SQLite RuntimeEvent</th>
            <td>
              <code>journal_mode=WAL</code> +
              <code>synchronous=FULL</code> + transactions
            </td>
            <td>Alternate canonical path; adds tool-journal tables</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row"><code>telemetry.json</code></th>
            <td>tmp + rename; no fsync</td>
            <td>Corrupt load <strong>refuses to overwrite</strong></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <blockquote class="pull">
      “Written to disk” ≠ “crash-safe.” Calling Session append or artifact rename fsync-durable is a
      classic authority mix-up.
    </blockquote>

    <h3 id="jsonl-repair" class="subhead">JSONL tail-repair protocol</h3>
    <p>
      Repair is <strong>embedded in the next <code>appendJsonl</code></strong> — there is no standalone
      CLI. If the file does not end with <code>\n</code> before append:
    </p>
    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li><code>findTrailingRecordStart</code> reverse-scans to the prior record start.</li>
      <li>
        <code>classifyJsonRecord(tail)</code> (<code>json-prefix.ts</code>) returns
        <code>complete | incomplete-prefix | invalid</code> — comment locks: whether missing only
        trailing bytes could make valid JSON.
      </li>
      <li><code>complete</code> → add a <code>\n</code> separator, then append.</li>
      <li>
        <code>incomplete-prefix</code> → <code>truncate(tailStart)</code> + <code>sync</code>, then
        append; truncating into the header with <code>requireExistingRecord</code> throws
        <code>Cannot repair a truncated JSONL document header</code>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>invalid</code> → throw
        <code>Cannot append after an invalid JSONL tail record</code> (fail closed).
      </li>
    </ol>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Read paths on torn tails" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Read path</th>
            <th scope="col">Torn / corrupt behavior</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Ordinary Session read</th>
            <td>
              Incomplete final line may be skipped; other corrupt → soft
              <code>system_note</code>
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">
              <code>readMessagesForRecovery</code> /
              <code>readEventsForRecovery</code>
            </th>
            <td><strong>Throw strictly</strong> (with line)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Phase0 prefix decision</th>
            <td>
              A torn JSON row is storage corruption — <strong>not</strong> a legal committed prefix
            </td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>
      Specimens: <code>execution-stores.test.ts</code> (unterminated tail repaired before the next
      durable append); <code>jsonl-append</code> / recovery-read tests. The Phase0 harness does
      <strong>not</strong> claim power-loss / OS-level fsync coverage — see maka’s crash-contract docs.
    </p>

    <h3 id="runtime-dual" class="subhead">RuntimeEvent dual backplane: JSONL vs SQLite</h3>
    <p>
      Default is per-run <code>runtime-events.jsonl</code>. When <code>runtime.sqlite</code> is present
      at the root, <code>openRuntimeEventPersistence</code> may use
      <code>SqliteRuntimeStore</code> (schema v4):
    </p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        Tables: <code>runtime_events</code> (PK <code>event_id</code>;
        <code>UNIQUE(invocation_id, event_seq)</code>) · <code>tool_journal_events</code> ·
        <code>tool_operations</code> · <code>runtime_partial_snapshots</code> ·
        <code>runtime_import_sources</code>
      </li>
      <li>
        Store pins: <code>durability = 'canonical'</code>;
        <code>toolBoundaryProtocol = 't1_after_preflight_v1'</code>
      </li>
      <li>
        Same terminal barrier: only a final terminal RuntimeEvent may
        <code>ensureTerminalRuntimeEventDurable</code>
      </li>
      <li>
        Migration: <code>BEGIN IMMEDIATE</code> → SQL → <code>user_version</code> →
        <code>COMMIT</code>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The SQLite path additionally carries the tool journal (T1/T2 boundary projection). JSONL and
      SQLite are <strong>alternate canonicals</strong> — not dual-write replication. Teach the dual
      honestly; do not invent an active-active story.
    </p>
    <h4 class="subhead">Sticky migration: <code>MAKA_RUNTIME_SQLITE_CANONICAL</code> is not a toggle</h4>
    <p>
      <code>openRuntimeEventPersistence(&#123; workspaceRoot, sqliteCanonical &#125;)</code> (
      <code>runtime-event-transfer.ts</code>) decides:
    </p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        Only when <code>sqliteCanonical === false</code> <strong>and</strong>
        <code>runtime.sqlite</code> is absent at the root → JSONL.
      </li>
      <li>
        Otherwise (flag <code>1</code>, or the file already exists) → open SQLite and best-effort
        import the legacy <code>runtime-events.jsonl</code> tree (with source markers).
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      So <code>MAKA_RUNTIME_SQLITE_CANONICAL=1</code> is a <strong>workspace migration trigger</strong>:
      once <code>runtime.sqlite</code> exists, clearing the env var does not fall back to JSONL —
      otherwise SQLite-only events would vanish. The system <strong>never dual-writes</strong> two
      RuntimeEvent sources of truth. CLI wiring:
      <code>packages/cli/src/runtime-bootstrap.ts</code>; contract:
      <code>runtime-event-transfer.test.ts</code> (stickyCanonical).
    </p>
    <div class="stub">
      <p class="stub__tag">Tool journal Current vs Phase 3</p>
      <p>
        Phase 2 (Current, flag/file path): SQLite schema, T1/T2, <code>operationId</code>, CAS,
        partial snapshots, JSONL import/export, single canonical writer. Journal query states narrow
        to <code>prepared | outcome_committed</code>. Unmatched calls after crash still park via
        Phase0 — <strong>not</strong> automatic side-effect reconcile. Phase 3 Target: journal
        <code>indeterminate / reconciled / parked</code> writes, dedicated reconciler, recovery
        verification — not shipped; do not read unmarked proposals as product. Long draft:
        <code>docs/runtime-resume-tool-journal-design-draft.zh-CN.md</code> (ADR + code override older
        “journal as truth” wording).
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3 id="derived-stores" class="subhead">Derived / weaker-durability stores</h3>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Derived stores" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Store</th>
            <th scope="col">Role</th>
            <th scope="col">Durability honesty</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">task-ledger-store</th>
            <td>Session short-key todo events + <code>tasks.json</code> projection</td>
            <td><code>appendFile</code>; <strong>no</strong> appendJsonl/fsync</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">shell-run-store</th>
            <td>Per-run <code>state.jsonl</code> rewrite</td>
            <td>Live process in runtime manager; checkpoint without fsync</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">artifact-store</th>
            <td>Blob + <code>metadata.jsonl</code></td>
            <td>tmp+rename; a corrupt metadata line may skip then compact</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">usage-stats-store</th>
            <td>Read-only scan of session token/tool rows</td>
            <td>
              Does not write; Settings UI aggregate (see
              <a href="#usage-stores">#usage-stores</a>)
            </td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3 id="store-failures" class="subhead">Failure matrix</h3>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Store failure matrix" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Failure</th>
            <th scope="col">Behavior</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Unterminated JSONL tail</td>
            <td>Next append truncates incomplete-prefix</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Invalid JSONL tail</td>
            <td>Append rejected</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Corrupt durable line (strict read)</td>
            <td>Throw with line</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Terminal RuntimeEvent mismatch</td>
            <td>Throw (exists but payload differs)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Root identity drift</td>
            <td><code>StorageRootAuthorityError</code></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Concurrent same-key writes</td>
            <td><code>chainWrite</code> serializes</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Durable fsync failure</td>
            <td><code>DurableStoreWriteError</code>; Host may drain</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>
      Research outline: <code>docs/research/storage-ledgers-deep-outline.md</code> (#55 → Task #81).
    </p>

    <h3 id="runtime-host" class="subhead">Runtime-host: four-op thin gateway</h3>
    <p>
      <code>@maka/runtime-host</code> is an optional Desktop <strong>thin orchestration shell</strong> —
      not a full Runtime RPC surface, and not a multi-tenant remote SaaS boundary. Motive: elect a
      single-writer Host on local IPC, hold the storage lock / root-turn admission, and keep the tool
      loop / Permission UI inside server-only composition.
    </p>

    <h4 class="subhead">Trust boundary</h4>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="runtime-host trust boundary">Client → unix socket + hello
  → Host authenticates InteractiveRootOwner
  → Admission by HostLifecycleState + residency
  → Server-only composition: SessionManager + execution stores

Host owns: interactive write lock · registration · op admission · composition hook
Host does NOT own: tool-loop API · Permission UI op · full session CRUD · settings · shell runs</pre>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        Protocol constants: <code>RUNTIME_HOST_PROTOCOL_VERSION = 2</code>;
        <code>RUNTIME_HOST_MAX_FRAME_BYTES = 64 KiB</code>; newline-delimited JSON.
      </li>
      <li>
        Handshake: <code>ClientHello</code> → <code>accepted | incompatible | draining</code>;
        registration <code>kind: 'maka-runtime-host'</code>, <code>rootId</code> =
        <code>/^[a-f0-9]&#123;64&#125;$/</code>.
      </li>
      <li>
        Endpoint: POSIX socket (dir <code>0o700</code> / sock <code>0o600</code>) or Windows named
        pipe; uid + mode checked.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Hard test:</strong> <code>dependency-boundary.test.ts</code> —
        <code>protocol/</code> and <code>client/</code> must <strong>not</strong> import
        <code>@maka/runtime</code> / execution-stores; only <code>server/</code> may.
      </li>
      <li>Headless / CLI may <strong>bypass the Host entirely</strong> and talk to SessionManager.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4 class="subhead">Exactly four operations (<code>HOST_OPERATION_SPECS</code>)</h4>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Four-op contract" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Op</th>
            <th scope="col">Mode</th>
            <th scope="col">Admission</th>
            <th scope="col">Retry</th>
            <th scope="col">Purpose</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row"><code>host.status</code></th>
            <td>query</td>
            <td>bootstrap</td>
            <td>safe</td>
            <td>epoch · state · connections / ops / residencies</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row"><code>turn.start</code></th>
            <td>command</td>
            <td>session</td>
            <td>semantic</td>
            <td>
              <code>&#123;sessionId, turnId, text≤48KiB&#125;</code> →
              <code>TurnSnapshot</code>
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row"><code>turn.query</code></th>
            <td>query</td>
            <td>ready</td>
            <td>safe</td>
            <td>Poll the same TurnSnapshot</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row"><code>turn.stop</code></th>
            <td>control</td>
            <td>session</td>
            <td>semantic</td>
            <td>Cancel; requires <code>runId</code></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>
      Frame: <code>&#123; requestId, operation, input &#125;</code> →
      <code>ok: true, result</code> or <code>ok: false, error: &#123; code, message &#125;</code>.
      <code>TurnRunStatus</code>:
      <code>admitted → created → running → waiting_permission → completed|failed|cancelled</code>.
      Terminals carry <code>terminalEventId</code> (+ <code>failureClass</code> /
      <code>abortSource</code>).
    </p>
    <p>
      There is <strong>no</strong> messages / permission-decision / shell / sandbox op. Permission
      appears only as <code>waiting_permission</code> on the snapshot; tool authorization stays inside
      <code>SessionManager</code> / PermissionEngine. Sandbox executors live in
      <code>@maka/runtime</code>, not the host package.
    </p>

    <h4 class="subhead">Lifecycle and admission</h4>
    <p>
      Host states: <code>starting → recovering → ready → draining</code> (plus
      <code>containing</code>). Kernel <code>#beginOperation</code>:
    </p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>Non-bootstrap and state ≠ <code>ready</code> → <code>host_not_ready</code></li>
      <li>Commands while draining / shutting down → <code>host_draining</code></li>
      <li>
        <code>admission: 'session'</code> is further checked by
        <code>RootTurnCoordinator</code> for busy / archived
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <code>turn.start</code>: durable root-turn admission <strong>before</strong> Run creation.
      Admission durability failure → turn.start error <strong>and</strong> Host drain — do not sacrifice
      the single-writer ledger to “just start running.”
    </p>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Host failure codes" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Code / failure</th>
            <th scope="col">Client should</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><code>host_draining</code> / <code>host_not_ready</code></td>
            <td>Wait / re-spawn</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>session_busy</code></td>
            <td>One active root turn per session</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>session_archived</code></td>
            <td>Reject start</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Pre-start durable failure</td>
            <td>turn.start error + host drain</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Epoch mismatch</td>
            <td>Re-read registration</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>
      Research outline: <code>docs/research/runtime-host-gateway-deep-outline.md</code> (#57 → Task
      #81). Do not invent a fifth op.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="recovery"
    label="§01 · Recovery"
    title="What crash recovery repairs"
    lede="State repair ≠ Phase0 prefix plan ≠ Phase1 safe continuation. Do not collapse the three into “warm resume.”"
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig 8b · Three recovery layers: startup projection repair (default) · Phase0 decision over a committed prefix · Phase1 flag-gated safe continuation (fresh identity)."
      alt="Three columns: Startup repair, Phase0 plan, Phase1 continue."
    >
      <RecoveryLayersFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <h3 class="subhead">A. Startup state repair (default crash path)</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Does:</strong> scan non-terminal Runs + ledgers; detect stale model stream / tool tail /
      permission wait / corrupt ops; conservatively commit failed/cancelled and repair Session/Turn
      projections.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Does not:</strong> re-invoke the model mid-tool; warm-resume from the next line of a side
      effect; invent what the model “was about to do” without durable facts.
    </p>

    <h3 id="agent-run-recovery" class="subhead">A′. Two recovery authorities: AgentRun ≠ RuntimeEvent</h3>
    <p>
      Startup repair actually runs <strong>two</strong> classifiers. Collapsing them into “warm resume”
      loses both Session terminal repair and tool-boundary judgment.
    </p>
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig 8b′ · classifyAgentRunRecovery closes non-terminal AgentRuns; resolveRuntimeRecovery alone owns tool-boundary judgment."
      alt="Two columns: AgentRunRecovery vs RuntimeRecovery with different ledgers and outputs."
    >
      <AgentRunVsRuntimeRecoveryFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="AgentRunRecovery vs RuntimeRecovery" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col"></th>
            <th scope="col">AgentRunRecovery</th>
            <th scope="col">RuntimeRecovery</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Function</th>
            <td><code>classifyAgentRunRecovery</code></td>
            <td><code>resolveRuntimeRecovery</code></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Input ledger</th>
            <td><code>AgentRunHeader</code> + ops <code>AgentRunEvent[]</code></td>
            <td>Canonical <code>RuntimeEvent[]</code> prefix</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Question</th>
            <td>How to close a non-terminal Run conservatively?</td>
            <td>Where is the tool call / dispatch / response boundary?</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Typical output</th>
            <td>
              <code>failed</code> + <code>failureClass: app_restarted</code> + diagnostic (e.g.
              <code>tool_interrupted</code> · <code>stale_permission_wait</code> ·
              <code>run_interrupted</code>)
            </td>
            <td>
              <code>completed</code> · <code>indeterminate</code> ·
              <code>definitely_not_dispatched</code> · <code>corruption</code>
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Does not</th>
            <td>Judge whether unsettled tool ops may re-run</td>
            <td>Repair Session / Turn projections alone</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>
      Honest <code>SessionManager</code> order: prefer mapping an existing Runtime terminal fact into an
      AgentRun decision; otherwise run <code>classifyAgentRunRecovery</code>. Then
      <code>applyAgentRunRecovery</code> commits the terminal Run (may append a recovered terminal
      RuntimeEvent) and patches Turn state as needed — diagnostics carry <code>recovered: true</code>.
      This is <strong>not</strong> the Resolver: tool boundaries still answer only to
      <code>resolveRuntimeRecovery()</code> (see T1/T2 below).
    </p>

    <h3 class="subhead">B. Phase0 failpoint matrix</h3>
    <p>
      The production API is pure: committed <code>RuntimeEvent</code> prefix → ToolOperation projection →
      <code>ResumePlan</code> → <code>safe_replay</code> or <code>blocked</code>. The machine-readable
      catalog is <code>RUNTIME_RESUME_FAILPOINTS</code> (P0–P11). It <strong>deliberately does not
      pretend</strong> a future T1/T2 journal already exists — only the last fully committed RuntimeEvent
      prefix after a crash. A torn JSON row is storage corruption, not a legal prefix.
    </p>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Phase0 failpoint matrix" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">IDs</th>
            <th scope="col">Committed prefix</th>
            <th scope="col">Disposition</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">P0</th>
            <td><code>before_function_call</code></td>
            <td><code>safe_replay</code> (no tool op yet)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">P1–P4</th>
            <td><code>after_function_call</code></td>
            <td>
              <code>blocked</code> · <code>dangling_tool_state</code> · operation indeterminate;
              unpaired call omitted from provider replay
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">P5–P8</th>
            <td><code>after_function_response</code></td>
            <td><code>safe_replay</code> (call/response paired)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">P9–P11</th>
            <td><code>after_terminal_event</code></td>
            <td>Same tool decision as prior prefix; terminal fact stays in the canonical ledger</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>
      Expected high-water ≠ reopened prefix → always <code>runtime_offset_mismatch</code>. The SIGKILL
      process-crash harness pins all twelve points; it does not claim power-loss / fsync durability.
    </p>

    <h3 class="subhead">C. Phase1 safe-boundary continuation</h3>
    <p>
      Only when <code>MAKA_RUNTIME_SAFE_BOUNDARY_RESUME=1</code> does a host expose Safe resume /
      <code>/resume</code>. Continuation <strong>never</strong> revives an old provider stream / JS
      stack / OS process; it creates a fresh Invocation / Run / Turn, durably writes a
      continuation-start RuntimeEvent first, then feeds validated replay to the provider (no duplicate
      user message). Any missing or contradictory fact → <code>park</code>; execution revalidates
      immediately before start. This is single-process ownership, not distributed fencing.
    </p>

    <h3 id="t1-t2" class="subhead">D. T1 / T2 + RecoveryResolver triad</h3>
    <p>
      Phase0 deliberately speaks only of “the last fully committed RuntimeEvent prefix,” without
      pretending a journal already exists. The current SQLite durable path adds a separate
      <strong>tool-boundary protocol</strong>: after every preflight (args, availability, loop gate,
      permission, sandbox escalation) and <em>before</em> <code>tool.impl()</code>, Runtime must cross
      <strong>T1</strong>; after the implementation and <em>before</em> publishing a result to the model,
      it must cross <strong>T2</strong>. Sole decision authority is
      <code>resolveRuntimeRecovery()</code> — Planner / CLI / UI must not reassemble call / dispatch /
      response themselves.
    </p>

    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig 8c · T1 atomic prepare → impl → T2 CAS commit → Resolver reads the event prefix only; crash points match the inject harness."
      alt="Four stages: T1 prepare, impl, T2 outcome, RecoveryResolver; four crash failpoints below."
    >
      <T1T2BoundaryFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <h4 class="subhead">T1 ≠ function_call</h4>
    <p>
      A provider-visible <code>function_call</code> may commit while permission is still pending — it
      only means “the model requested a call.” <strong>T1</strong> is a distinct, non-model-visible
      RuntimeEvent:
    </p>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="toolDispatch shape">actions.toolDispatch = &#123;
  protocol: "t1_after_preflight_v1",
  operationId, providerToolCallId, toolName,
  canonicalArgsHash, recoveryMode
&#125;</pre>
    <p>
      Exact meaning: “Runtime entered the boundary where it is <strong>unsafe to assume implementation
      did not run</strong>” — not “side effects happened.”
      <code>prepareDurableToolAttempt</code> commits, via
      <code>RuntimeCommitSink.commitToolPrepared</code> in one transaction: the call (if absent), the
      dispatch event, a journal row <code>prepared</code>, and the <code>tool_operations</code>
      projection. T1 failure must block impl: tests pin <code>implementationCalls === 0</code> and no
      published <code>tool_result</code>. Another dispatcher already owning the same
      <code>operationId</code> (<code>created: false</code>) also blocks impl.
    </p>

    <h4 class="subhead">T2 and RuntimeCommitBoundaryError</h4>
    <p>
      Happy-path ordering is locked by the durable-boundary test as
      <code>['t1','impl','t2','published-result']</code>. T2 writes <code>function_response</code>
      through <code>commitToolOutcome</code>; SQLite compare-and-sets
      <code>current_state='prepared' AND result_event_id IS NULL</code> — a second writer throws, never
      silent double-writes. <code>RuntimeCommitBoundaryError</code> carries phase
      <code>'T1' | 'T2'</code>: ToolRuntime <strong>rethrows</strong> it instead of folding it into a
      synthetic tool result — a commit-boundary fault is a Runtime fault, not “the tool returned an
      error string.” On T2 failure, impl may already have run once, but the model still sees no
      published result (that side-effect window is Resolver <code>indeterminate</code>).
    </p>

    <h4 class="subhead">Protocol marker is a capability fact</h4>
    <p>
      <code>toolBoundary: t1_after_preflight_v1</code> is written only when the host
      <strong>actually wires</strong> a <code>RuntimeCommitSink</code>, and only on the run’s
      <strong>first</strong> canonical RuntimeEvent (initial user on a normal run; continuation-start on
      a continuation). Never invent it from a software version; JSONL / no-sink paths must not carry
      the marker; mid-run backfill is always <code>protocol_marker_invalid</code>. Illegal markers →
      <code>hasCorruption</code>; missing marker → interpret the whole run as legacy (missing dispatch
      never proves “definitely did not run”).
    </p>

    <h4 class="subhead">RecoveryResolver decision table (row-locked by tests)</h4>
    <p>
      RuntimeEvent is the sole canonical recovery fact; Tool Journal / <code>tool_operations</code>
      are rebuildable projections (ADR) — after wiping projections, rebuild from events must match;
      conflicts prefer RuntimeEvent and count as corruption.
    </p>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="RecoveryResolver decision table" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Fact combination</th>
            <th scope="col">status</th>
            <th scope="col">reason (test code)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">call + matching response (dispatch optional)</th>
            <td><code>completed</code></td>
            <td><code>matching_response</code> (incl. pre-T1 synthetic deny)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">call + dispatch, no response</th>
            <td><code>indeterminate</code></td>
            <td><code>dispatch_without_response</code> · <strong>no</strong> auto re-run</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">call, no dispatch/response, new-protocol marker</th>
            <td><code>definitely_not_dispatched</code></td>
            <td><code>new_protocol_before_dispatch</code></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Same, but legacy / unknown protocol</th>
            <td><code>indeterminate</code></td>
            <td><code>legacy_dispatch_unknown</code> (missing ≠ non-execution)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">orphan dispatch / orphan response</th>
            <td><code>corruption</code></td>
            <td><code>orphan_dispatch</code> / <code>orphan_response</code></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">duplicate dispatch / response</th>
            <td><code>corruption</code></td>
            <td><code>duplicate_dispatch</code> / <code>duplicate_response</code></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">name / operationId / toolCallId drift</th>
            <td><code>corruption</code></td>
            <td><code>identity_conflict</code></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">illegal / misplaced protocol marker</th>
            <td>issues + corruption</td>
            <td><code>protocol_marker_invalid</code></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h4 class="subhead">SQLite crash harness (orthogonal to the Phase0 catalog)</h4>
    <p>
      Phase0 P0–P11 decide at the “event prefix” grain; the durable sink additionally pins
      in-transaction points with a real child-process <code>SIGKILL</code>
      (<code>sqlite-runtime-crash.test.ts</code>):
    </p>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="T1/T2 crash points" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Inject</th>
            <th scope="col">Facts after reopen</th>
            <th scope="col">Resolver meaning</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row"><code>inside_t1</code></th>
            <td>Zero events, zero unsettled ops (full rollback)</td>
            <td>No tool-boundary facts</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row"><code>after_effect</code> (after T1; side effects possible)</th>
            <td>Op stays <code>prepared</code>; listed by <code>listUnsettledToolOperations</code></td>
            <td><code>indeterminate</code> / reconcile_required</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row"><code>inside_t2</code></th>
            <td>T1 survives; op still <code>prepared</code> (T2 is atomic — no half response)</td>
            <td>Same as dispatch_without_response</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row"><code>after_t2</code></th>
            <td><code>outcome_committed</code>; nothing unsettled</td>
            <td><code>completed</code></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>
      Journal state is narrowed to the write paths that exist today:
      <code>prepared | outcome_committed</code>. Future indeterminate / reconciled query states need
      matching RuntimeEvents first — never a second parallel state machine.
    </p>

    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">Evolution aside · mechanism</p>
      <p>
        AgentRun startup classifier: commit <code>06112db9</code> (Recover sessions from AgentRun
        ledger) · <code>agent-run-recovery.ts</code>. Durable safe-boundary phases (resolver / sink /
        sqlite T1–T2):
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/1223")}>maka:pr:1223</a>. Contract = tests:
        <code>recovery-resolver.test.ts</code> (row-by-row),
        <code>tool-runtime-durable-boundary.test.ts</code> (T1 fail → zero impl; order
