  </Section>

  <Section
    id="replay"
    label="§01 · Replay"
    title="Three meanings of “replay the state space”"
    lede="Semantic replay is Current; do not smuggle wire-level determinism as a delivered promise."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig 9 · Semantic replay (Current) ≠ Provider-native (capability-gated) ≠ Bit-exact wire (Target) — the last opens the #request-shape cost spine."
      alt="Three columns: Semantic replay, Provider-native, Bit-exact wire pointing to request-shape."
    >
      <ReplayLayersFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li>
        <strong>Semantic replay (Current)</strong> — given the ledger, rebuild text, thinking, tool
        pairing, permissions, usage, and terminal facts; next-turn model history and completed Session
        read models prefer this construction.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Provider-native replay (capability-gated)</strong> — providers differ on tool history
        / signed thinking; plan first, then choose native, text-only, or explicit degradation.
        Replayable ≠ dumping JSONL into an arbitrary model.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Bit-exact wire replay (Target / not claimed)</strong> — today’s Event Log stores
        canonical message semantics, not a full snapshot of every HTTP byte. System prompt, tool
        schema, options, and projection policy still participate in request generation. The cost
        spine teaches the <strong>diagnostic model</strong> of that materialization — not a claim that
        the ledger already holds a full wire snapshot. See the next section.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="request-shape"
    label="§01 · Request shape"
    title="What the provider sees is not what the ledger stores as messages"
    lede="Cost spine: measure hit/miss/write before celebrating shorter prompts. prefixHash is Maka-local diagnostics — not the provider cache key."
  >
    <p>
      Cost discipline mounts on the existing execution spine — not a separate
      <code>CostRuntime</code> (design judgment from archive
      <code>deepseek-reasonix-cost-runtime-design.md</code>; open decisions defer to Current code). An
      archived note (extract durable ideas; <strong>not</strong> Current authority) left a pressure
      scene: lowering the history budget cut total input tokens while
      <strong>cache miss and estimated cost rose</strong>. The root is often not “the model got more
      expensive,” but durable-prefix pollution (cwd/date), active tool-schema churn, or history
      projection change — and local <code>prefixHash</code> / <code>requestShapeHash</code> only
      diagnose Maka’s own stable serialization. They are <strong>not</strong> DeepSeek’s (or any
      provider’s) internal cache key.
    </p>

    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig 10 · Durable prefix (prefixHash) nested inside full request shape (requestShapeHash); volatile turn-tail facts must not pollute the durable system prompt."
      alt="Nested rectangles: durable prefix inside request shape; turn tail lists cwd/date volatility."
    >
      <PrefixVsShape />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Provider-visible request structure">provider-visible request
  durable prefix
    model / provider identity
    system prompt
    provider options
    active tool schema
  history projection          # prior messages view
  current user content
  turn tail                   # volatile facts</pre>

    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="durable vs turn tail" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Goes in durable system prompt</th>
            <th scope="col">Goes in turn tail</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Stable behavior rules</td>
            <td>Current cwd</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Long-lived user preferences</td>
            <td>Git status</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Workspace / skills instructions</td>
            <td>Date / platform</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Opt-in stable local memory</td>
            <td>Fresh memory updates this Turn</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">Local memory · Current companion</p>
      <p>
        The two-switch model (<code>enabled</code> / <code>agentReadEnabled</code> default OFF) and
        <code>MEMORY.md</code> inject boundary are Current Desktop contracts — not implicit durable
        memory. Full whitebox (disk perms, safe_mode, prefix vs turn-tail, failure modes):
        <a href={localePath("en", "guides/local-memory")}>/guides/local-memory</a>. Archive history
        aside: <code>docs/research/memory-whitebox-archive-delta.md</code>.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <h3 id="prefix-vs-tail" class="subhead">Durable prefix vs turn tail</h3>
    <p>
      Failure story: the team believes “the system prompt is unchanged” while date/cwd rewrite it
      every Turn → <code>prefixHash</code> chatters → miss rises → root cause is misattributed to
      history. Volatile facts belong in the turn tail, not the durable prefix.
    </p>

    <h3 id="hashes" class="subhead"><code>prefixHash</code> and <code>requestShapeHash</code></h3>
    <p>From Current <code>computeRequestShapeDiagnostic</code>:</p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        <strong><code>prefixHash</code></strong> ← stableHash of
        <code>modelProviderHash</code> · <code>systemPromptHash</code> ·
        <code>providerOptionsHash</code> · <code>toolSchemaHash</code> (active/visible tools only)
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><code>requestShapeHash</code></strong> ← the above plus
        <code>historyProjectionHash</code>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Change reason classifiers" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Reason</th>
            <th scope="col">Typical meaning</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">first_turn</th>
            <td>No prior diagnostic</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">model_or_provider_changed</th>
            <td>Connection / model identity</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">system_prompt_changed</th>
            <td>Durable prompt bytes</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">tool_schema_changed etc.</th>
            <td>Active schema / economy load</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">provider_options_changed</th>
            <td>Options blob</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">history_projection_changed</th>
            <td>Prior messages view (compact / prune / growth)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">stable</th>
            <td>No component change detected</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>
      <strong>These are Maka-local diagnostics.</strong> The provider may hash and segment
      differently. Advanced aside: <code>capturePreparedProviderRequest</code> segment order (tools →
      system → messages) and first-diff help deeper triage, but are not the chapter’s first viewport.
    </p>

    <h3 id="usage-split" class="subhead">Cache hit / miss / write / output / reasoning</h3>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Usage counters" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Counter</th>
            <th scope="col">Role</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">cache hit</th>
            <td>Provider-reported reused input</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">cache miss</th>
            <td>Fresh input — <strong>check provenance</strong></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">cache write</th>
            <td>Tokens written into provider cache</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">output</th>
            <td>Completion</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">reasoning</th>
            <td>Separate from ordinary output when the provider exposes it</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>
      Miss provenance: use a provider-native miss field when present; otherwise
      <strong>derived</strong>: <code>max(0, input − hit − write)</code> with
      <code>cacheMissInputSource = derived</code>. Never invent counters when usage is missing —
      record a diagnostic gap. Keep cost teaching light: miss / read / write / output may have
      different unit prices; do not pretend a single “input price” explains DeepSeek-class bills.
    </p>

    <h3 id="attribution" class="subhead">Attribution ladder when miss rises</h3>
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig 11 · Walk six questions in order when miss rises; branch on prefix stable vs prefix moved."
      alt="Vertical attribution ladder with side branches for prefix stable / prefix moved."
    >
      <AttributionLadder />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Observation patterns" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Observation</th>
            <th scope="col">Likely story</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><code>prefixHash</code> stable, <code>requestShapeHash</code> changed</td>
            <td>History/tail churn; prefix locality may still help</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>prefixHash</code> changed + system_prompt_changed</td>
            <td>Placement bug or intentional prompt edit</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>prefixHash</code> changed + tool schema reason</td>
            <td>Economy load or catalog churn</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Total input ↓ but miss ↑</td>
            <td>Classic false win — measure before celebrating</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3 id="tool-economy" class="subhead">providerTools ≠ activeTools</h3>
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig 12 · Full providerTools (dispatch) vs wire-visible activeTools (advertise); load_tools changes the visible set; PermissionEngine authorizes orthogonally."
      alt="Full registry, active wire set, load_tools arrow, orthogonal PermissionEngine."
    >
      <ActiveVsRegistry />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <p>
      On the cost spine there are two <strong>non-interchangeable</strong> axes — typed in the return
      value of <code>canonicalizeToolSet</code>:
    </p>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="dispatch vs advertise" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Axis</th>
            <th scope="col">Carrier</th>
            <th scope="col">Changes when</th>
            <th scope="col">Affects</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Dispatch</td>
            <td><code>providerTools: MakaTool[]</code></td>
            <td>Catalog composition (+ connector + invalid)</td>
            <td>Local execute / repair targets</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Advertise / wire</td>
            <td><code>activeTools: string[]</code></td>
            <td>Economy groups + <code>load_tools</code> + <code>prepareStep</code></td>
            <td>Provider schemas, <code>toolSchemaHash</code>, <code>prefixHash</code></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Authorize</td>
            <td>PermissionEngine</td>
            <td>User / policy grants</td>
            <td>Whether an advertised call may run</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="canonicalizeToolSet">visibleTools = tools \ {'{'}invalid{'}'} , sorted by name
activeTools  = filter(visibleTools, activeNames?)   # omit ⇒ full surface
providerTools = [...visibleTools, invalid]         # invalid never advertised</pre>
    <p>
      <strong>Dispatch never depends on advertisement visibility.</strong> A gated-and-unloaded tool
      stays in <code>providerTools</code> so it remains executable once its group loads. The AI SDK
      serializes the <code>activeTools</code> subset; unloaded group schemas stay off the wire. The
      repair / invalid tool is present in <code>providerTools</code> but
      <strong>never</strong> enters <code>activeTools</code>.
    </p>
    <h4 class="subhead">When economy actually bites</h4>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        Effective economy = <code>config.economy === true</code> <strong>and</strong>
        <code>gatedNames.size &gt; 0</code>. Flag on but nothing to hide →
        <strong>falls back to full surface</strong> (no connector, no gating, no diagnostics) — economy
        is inert.
      </li>
      <li>
        Economy mode: step-0 visible = ungrouped tools ∪ <code>load_tools</code>; group tools stay
        hidden until the connector activates. Same-turn expansion is monotonic via
        <code>prepareStep</code>; cross-turn survival is ledger seed only.
      </li>
      <li>
        Historical connector names (<code>load_tool</code> / <code>connect_tool_source</code>) are
        <strong>seed-only</strong> from the durable ledger; same-turn activation honors only live
        <code>load_tools</code>.
      </li>
      <li>
        Execute-boundary: a tool absent from the step-start active snapshot cannot be called in that
        step.
      </li>
      <li><strong>Load ≠ permission grant.</strong> Advertise, load, and authorize are three different acts.</li>
    </ul>
    <h4 class="subhead"><code>toolSchemaHash</code> eats the visible subset only</h4>
    <p>
      <code>computeRequestShapeDiagnostic</code> stableHashes
      <code>providerVisibleTools(providerTools, activeTools)</code> — an inactive deferred tool’s schema
      edit must <strong>not</strong> false-fire <code>tool_schema_changed</code>; a real
      <code>load_tools</code> activation <strong>must</strong> move the hash so loads are distinguishable
      from catalog churn. Char diagnostics measure the same visible subset. Mid-turn capacity triggers
      may count same-turn schema growth into the next-request estimate (see
      <a href={localePath("en", "chapters/03-compaction-is-a-projection") + "#capacity-shaping"}
        >§03 · capacity-shaping</a
      >) — still about the outgoing request, not a second cache key.
    </p>
    <p>
      Specimens: <code>request-shape.test.ts</code> (inactive drift ignored / activation changes hash);
      <code>tool-availability.test.ts</code> (full / economy / inert / prepareStep / ledger seed).
    </p>

    <h3 id="usage-stores" class="subhead">Usage dual-store, pricing, and capture</h3>
    <p>
      Hit/miss/write diagnostics (above) answer “why did the request shape move?” The three paths below
      answer <strong>different questions</strong> — do not collapse them into “the billing truth”:
    </p>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Three usage paths" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Store / path</th>
            <th scope="col">Written by</th>
            <th scope="col">Read by</th>
            <th scope="col">Role</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">
              <code>telemetry.json</code> (TelemetryRepo)
            </th>
            <td>
              <code>recordLlmCall</code> /
              <code>recordToolInvocation</code>
            </td>
            <td>summary / buckets / logs / pricing CRUD</td>
            <td>Full usage records + <code>pricingOverrides</code></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Session JSONL → usage-stats-store</th>
            <td>
              Runtime materializes <code>token_usage</code> / tool rows (parallel to telemetry)
            </td>
            <td>Settings <code>usageStats()</code></td>
            <td>
              Aggregates <code>costUsd</code> already on the transcript;
              does <strong>not</strong> read telemetry.json; <code>pricing: []</code>
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">provider_request_capture</th>
            <td>Artifact body + AgentRun ledger metadata</td>
            <td>Headless trace / debug</td>
            <td>
              Serialized request evidence; hidden by default in desktop UI;
              <strong>≠</strong> billing telemetry; ≠ provider cache key
            </td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h4 class="subhead">Pricing key and computeCost</h4>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        Pricing key = <code>providerId:modelId</code>. Lookup = override ??
        <code>getBuiltinPricing</code>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>computeCost</code>: cacheMiss / cacheRead / cacheWrite / output components × unit price /
        1e6; <strong>missing unit price → all $0</strong>, not an error.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>recordLlmCall</code> is async best-effort via <code>queueMicrotask</code>; failures
        <code>console.error</code> and must <strong>not</strong> block the turn.
      </li>
      <li>
        When the provider omits native miss:
        <code>cacheMissInputSource: 'derived'</code> =
        <code>max(0, input − hit − write)</code>. Local <code>prefixHash</code> /
        <code>requestShapeHash</code> enter diagnostic fields only — they
        <strong>do not</strong> drive the price formula.
      </li>
      <li>
        Builtin pricing is a dated snapshot; special plans need overrides. Do not pretend it is always
        current.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h4 class="subhead">Capture pipeline (≠ billing)</h4>
    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li>
        Provider seam: <code>secretFreeParams</code> strips <code>abortSignal</code> and
        <code>headers</code> — comment locks “Exact secret-free model-call parameters.”
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>persistProviderRequestCaptureArtifact</code>: full <code>serializedRequest</code> into an
        artifact (<code>source: 'provider_request_capture'</code>).
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>AgentRun.recordProviderRequestCapture</code>: ledger
        <strong>deliberately omits</strong> the body — metadata + <code>artifactId</code> only; written
        with <code>durable: true</code>.
      </li>
      <li>Order: artifact first, then ledger (body stripped). Attempt records may be best-effort.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      WebSearch query strings are scrubbed at the <code>recordToolInvocation</code>
      <code>argsSummary</code> boundary (privacy contract; see
      <code>web-search-telemetry-scrub-contract.test.ts</code>).
    </p>
    <blockquote class="pull">
      Telemetry books · Session aggregates for UI · Capture for debug/replay — three questions, three
      answers; collapsing them into “billing truth” is always wrong.
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      Research outline: <code>docs/research/usage-cost-telemetry-deep-outline.md</code> (#61 → Task
      #81). Optional <code>/guides/cost</code> remains fog — do not open it while this section teaches
      the protocol.
    </p>

    <h3 id="cost-fail-open" class="subhead">Never delete facts to chase cache</h3>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>§02: archive fail → keep the full tool result message.</li>
      <li>§03: compact fail → safe source-derived context; no false coverage.</li>
      <li>Hydration fail → never fake raw bytes.</li>
      <li>
        A cache hit is never a reason to delete ledger facts or skip integrity checks.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <blockquote class="pull">
      Optimize the provider-visible view; never destroy the source to chase a hit rate.
    </blockquote>

