  <Section
    id="skills"
    label="§01 · Skills"
    title="The skill catalog is a budgeted advertisement — not always-on manuals"
    lede="Catalog enters the system prompt; bodies lazy-load. allowed-tools never grants."
  >
    <p>
      Maka keeps skill bodies in <code>SKILL.md</code> out of the always-on system prompt. The prompt
      carries only a bounded <strong>catalog</strong>; when a task matches, the read-only
      <code>Skill</code> tool (or explicit <code>/skill:</code> / invocation chips) loads full
      instructions. The contract is <code>docs/skill-catalog-policy.md</code>, locked by
      <code>packages/runtime/src/skills.ts</code> / <code>skill-invocation.ts</code>.
    </p>
    <h3 class="subhead">Discover → gate → budget</h3>
    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li>
        Scan in source precedence: project → workspace compatibility paths → user; duplicate ids use
        <strong>first-found wins</strong>; within one directory, order by display name.
      </li>
      <li>Exclude disabled skills.</li>
      <li>
        When the host supplies capabilities, hide skills missing explicit
        <code>required-tools</code> / <code>required-capabilities</code>.
        <code>allowed-tools</code> / <code>declaredTools</code> are informational only — they
        <strong>never grant</strong>.
      </li>
      <li>
        Fill the catalog until budget: 2% of the model context window, clamped to about 4,000–8,000
        estimated tokens (four characters per token); if the window is unknown, fall back to
        <code>MAX_SKILLS_PROMPT_CHARS = 18000</code>. The window is an <strong>explicit prompt
        input</strong>, not an implicit provider lookup inside the scanner.
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Omitted entries still list their ids: omission affects advertisement only — enabled,
      host-compatible skills remain loadable by id/name. The host gate runs <strong>before</strong>
      budget truncation so incompatible skills are never advertised.
    </p>
    <h3 class="subhead">Explicit invocation and the trust frame</h3>
    <p>
      <code>composeSkillInvocationMessage</code> injects <code>&lt;invoked-skill&gt;</code> blocks
      before user text and states: skill content ranks below system / developer / safety /
      permission; it cannot grant tools, weaken prompts, reveal secrets, or override higher-priority
      instructions; do not call <code>Skill</code> again for skills already loaded this turn.
      Per-request load failures do not block other invocations or the send itself.
    </p>
    <div class="stub">
      <p class="stub__tag">Runtime vs Desktop</p>
      <p>
        Runtime owns scan, catalog, lazy load, and invocation composition. Desktop lock / provenance /
        managed-source / bundled catalog is product governance — not a second runtime truth. The 29
        bundled <code>SKILL.md</code> bodies are product content; this site teaches the
        <strong>mechanism</strong>, not those essays as Destination.
      </p>
    </div>
    <h3 id="skills-failure" class="subhead">Failure stories</h3>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Skills failure matrix" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Situation</th>
            <th scope="col">Result</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Skill disabled</td>
            <td>Excluded from catalog and invoke list</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Host missing <code>required-tools</code> / capabilities</td>
            <td>Hidden (<code>required_tools_missing</code>); not advertised</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Budget exceeded</td>
            <td>Later ads omitted; ids listed; still loadable by id</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Unknown invoke name</td>
            <td>Per-request failure; others proceed</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Body too large / validation fail</td>
            <td>Load fail; do not pretend injection succeeded</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>allowed-tools: Bash</code> claim</td>
            <td>Informational only; PermissionEngine still gates</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Duplicate id across sources</td>
            <td>First-found wins</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">Verification</p>
      <p>
        Contract tests: <code>packages/runtime/src/__tests__/skills.test.ts</code>,
        <code>skill-invocation.test.ts</code>. Outline:
        <code>docs/research/skill-catalog-policy-deep-outline.md</code>.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="mcp"
    label="§01 · MCP"
    title="MCP projects into the same ToolRuntime — not a second agent loop"
    lede="Manager connects remotes; the adapter becomes MakaTool; permission / log / abort are reused."
  >
    <p>
      MCP must reuse the existing <code>MakaTool</code> execution boundary:
      <code>McpClientManager</code> (<code>@maka/mcp</code>) owns connect, discovery, and calls;
      <code>buildMcpTools</code> projects remote tools into dynamic <code>MakaTool[]</code>. MCP then
      inherits PermissionEngine, Runtime event log, telemetry, result persistence, abort, and loop
      gates — there is no parallel “MCP agent.”
    </p>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="MCP data flow">Desktop IPC → McpConfigStore (mcp.json)
  → McpClientManager (stdio | Streamable HTTP | SSE)
  → buildMcpTools → AiSdkBackend
  → ToolRuntime (permission + events + telemetry)
  → Manager.callTool</pre>
    <h3 class="subhead">Trust and naming</h3>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        Every MCP tool uses <code>categoryHint: network_send</code>. Server
        <code>readOnlyHint</code> is an <strong>untrusted advisory</strong> and cannot lower
        permission policy; explore mode fails closed.
      </li>
      <li>
        Proxy names are <code>mcp__&#123;serverId&#125;__&#123;toolName&#125;</code>; beyond 64
        characters a stable hash suffix is used, with collision detection.
      </li>
      <li>
        stdio inherits only an allowlisted env; explicit <code>env</code> overrides last. The
        renderer <strong>never</strong> holds an MCP client or child process.
      </li>
      <li>
        Rich output has aggregate bounds on text / images / summaries; audio, resource blobs, and
        unknown payloads are not dumped into model context.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <h3 class="subhead">Config lifecycle</h3>
    <p>
      Workspace <code>mcp.json</code> uses a shared <code>mcpServers</code> map; a full normalized
      fingerprint drives reconcile — only changed servers move. Written config ≠ authorized ≠
      connected: setup templates land disabled until the user completes setup and enables them.
      After config changes or <code>notifications/tools/list_changed</code>, reconcile first, then
      invalidate backend caches; the active turn is not force-killed — the old backend releases after
      the last active run, and the next turn sees the new tool snapshot. Connected MCP tools join the
      visible schema and therefore affect <a href="#tool-economy">#tool-economy</a>’s
      <code>toolSchemaHash</code>.
    </p>
    <div class="stub">
      <p class="stub__tag">V1 vs V2</p>
      <p>
        V1 (shipped): stdio / Streamable HTTP / SSE, paginated list, list_changed, timeouts/abort,
        Desktop “Extensions &gt; MCP” CRUD. V2 backlog: OAuth 2.1 + PKCE, resources UI, loopback
        proxy, finer trusted-server policy — do not read backlog as Current.
      </p>
    </div>
    <h3 id="mcp-failure" class="subhead">Failure stories</h3>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="MCP failure matrix" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Situation</th>
            <th scope="col">Result</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Concurrent connect same server</td>
            <td>Single active promise</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Connect fail</td>
            <td>Close half-open client/transport; status error</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>tools/list_changed</code></td>
            <td>Refresh that server’s tool cache only</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Config fingerprint change</td>
            <td>Disconnect + reconnect affected server</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Tool call abort</td>
            <td>Caller abort &gt; timeout</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>MCP <code>isError</code></td>
            <td>Maka error path with server/tool context</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>stdio crash</td>
            <td>stderr tail ≤10 lines, redacted/truncated</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Proxy name collision</td>
            <td>Throw at build time</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>readOnlyHint: true</code> on mutating tool</td>
            <td>Still <code>network_send</code>; explore fail-closed</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Cancel mid-install</td>
            <td>No config resurrection; tools invisible</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>
      Desktop Computer Use is an orthogonal contract (observation frames / cua-driver) — see
      <a href={localePath("en", "guides/computer-use")}>/guides/computer-use</a>.
    </p>
